    <exercises xml:id="practice-polynomial-division-algorithm" permid="RdQ">
      <title>Practice Problems</title>
      <exercise permid="XCW">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Vlg">
            In <m>\Z_7[x]</m>, find the quotient and remainder as in the division algorithm for <m>a(x) = 5x^3 + 6x^2 - 3x + 4</m> and <m>b(x) = x-2</m>.  Then verify that <m>r(x)</m> is <m>a(2)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Bzt">
          <p permid="suc">
            <m>5x^3 + 6x^2 - 3x + 4 = (5x^2 + 2x + 1)(x-2) + 6</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="DKf">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Bsp">
            In <m>\Z_5[x]</m>, find the quotient and remainder as in the division algorithm for <m>a(x) = 4x^5 - x^3 +x^2 + 4</m> and <m>b(x) = x^3-2</m>.  
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="hGC">
          <p permid="YBl">
            <m>4x^5 - x^3 +x^2 + 4 = (4x^2 + 4)(x^3 +3) + 4x^2 + 2</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="jRo">
        <statement>
          <p permid="hzy">
            Suppose the ideal <m>J</m> of <m>\Z</m> is the smallest ideal that contains both 231 and 429.  Find a single element <m>p \in \Z</m> such that <m>J = \langle p \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="NNL">
          <p permid="EIu">
            We have <m>J = \langle 33 \rangle</m>.  Note that <m>\langle 3 \rangle</m> and <m>\langle 11 \rangle</m> and <m>\langle 1 \rangle</m> are also ideals that contains 231 and 429, but these are larger ideals.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="PYx">
        <statement>
          <p permid="NGH">
            Suppose the ideal <m>J</m> of <m>\Q[x]</m> is the smallest ideal that contains both <m>x^2 - 2x - 3</m> and <m>x^3 - 5x^2 + 6x</m>.  Find a single element <m>p \in \Q[x]</m> such that <m>J = \langle p \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="acd">
          <p permid="uTj">
            Factor the polynomials
          </p>
        </hint>
        <solution permid="tUU">
          <p permid="kPD">
            The polynomials factor as <m>(x-1)(x-3)</m> and <m>x(x-2)(x-3)</m>.  Thus the greatest common divisor for the two polynomials is <m>x-3</m> so both are in the ideal <m>\langle x-3\rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="wfG">
        <statement>
          <p permid="tNQ">
            Suppose the ideal  <m>J</m> of <m>\Z_5[x]</m> is the smallest ideal that contains both <m>2x^7 + 4</m> and <m>x^7 + 1</m>.  Find a single element <m>p \in \Z_5[x]</m> such that <m>J = \langle p \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Gjm">
          <p permid="QWM">
            Note that if the ideal contains these polynomials then it also contains <m>2x^7 + 2</m> and thus also <m>2x^7 + 4 - (2x^7 + 2) = 2</m>, and then also 1 (since <m>2\cdot 3 \in J</m> too).  Thus <m>J = \langle 1 \rangle = \Z_5[x]</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="cmP">
        <statement>
          <p permid="ZUZ">
            Let <m>J</m> be an ideal that contains polynomials <m>a(x)</m> and <m>b(x)</m> in <m>F[x]</m> for some field <m>F</m>.  If <m>r(x)</m> is the remainder when <m>a(x)</m> is divided by <m>b(x)</m>, prove that <m>r(x)</m> is also in the ideal <m>J</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="mqv">
          <p permid="xdV">
            By the division algorithm, <m>a(x) = q(x)b(x) + r(x)</m>, which in turn means that <m>a(x) - q(x)b(x) = r(x)</m>.  But <m>-q(x)b(x) \ in J</m> (since <m>J</m> absorbs products) and thus so is <m>a(x) - q(x)b(x) = r(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="ItY">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Gci">
            In the previous problem you proved that if <m>a(x), b(x) \in J</m> and <m>a(x) = q(x)b(x) + r(x)</m>, then <m>r(x) \in J</m>.  If you then apply the division algorithm again, to <m>b(x)</m> and <m>r(x)</m>, to find <m>b(x) = q'(x)r(x) + r'(x)</m>, you would have that <m>r'(x) \in J</m> as well.
          </p>
          <p permid="mjr">
            What would happen if you kept doing this?  Would it go on forever?  If it stops, how would it?  And what does this have to do with the GCD?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="SxE">
          <p permid="dle">
            We know that the process cannot go on forever, since each time the new remainder is smaller than the previous remainder (the new divisor).  Thus eventually this must stop (by having a remainder of zero).
          </p>
          <p permid="Jsn">
            The last non-zero remainder will in fact be the greatest common divisor of <m>a(x)</m> and <m>b(x)</m>, since it will be the smallest degree polynomial in the ideal.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="oBh">
        <statement>
          <p permid="SqA">
            Does <m>3x^3 - 4x^2 - x + 4</m>, as a polynomial in <m>\Z_5[x]</m> have any roots?  What does this tell you about whether the polynomial can factor in <m>\Z_5[x]</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="yEN">
          <p permid="pzw">
            There are no roots.  Since any factorization would need to include a linear term, this says that the polynomial is irreducible.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="UIq">
        <statement>
          <p permid="yxJ">
            Find two different factorizations of <m>x^2 + x + 8</m> in <m>\Z_{10}[x]</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="eLW">
          <p permid="bas">
            One factorization is <m>(x+2)(x+9)</m>.  Are there other ways to multiply to <m>8</m> in <m>\Z_{10}</m>?
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>

    </exercises>


