    <exercises xml:id="practice-irreducible-polynomials" permid="dsi">
      <title>Practice Problems</title>

      <exercise permid="tla">
        <statement>
          <p permid="qTk">
          True or false: <m>3x+ 9</m> is irreducible in <m>\Q[x]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="KTf">
          <p permid="VGF">
          True.  While <m>3x+9 = 3(x+3)</m>, we have not written the polynomial as  the product of two polynomials of smaller degree.  If fact, all degree 1 polynomials in <m>F[x]</m> were <m>F</m> is a field are irreducible because you can't have two degree 0 polynomials multiply to be a degree 1 polynomial.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="Zsj">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Xat">
          Factor <m>x+2</m> in <m>\Z_6[x]</m> into two degree 1 polynomials.  Does this mean that <m>x+2</m> is not irreducible?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="rao">
          <p permid="BNO">
          We have <m>x+2 = (2x+1)(3x+2)</m>.  This is strange.  Under our definition, the polynomial is still irreducible, but it does now factor into polynomials of positive degree (which would be an equivalent definition if the coefficients came from a field).
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>


      <exercise permid="Fzs">
        <statement>
          <p permid="DhC">
          Factor the polynomial <m>x^5 - 6x^3 - 6x^2 - 7x - 6</m> over <m>\Q</m> into irreducible factors (and explain how you know the irreducible factors are irreducible).
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Xhx">
          <p permid="hUX">
          Using either the corollary to Gauss's lemma or the rational roots theorem, we know the only possible roots are <m>\pm 1</m>,            <m>\pm 2</m>,            <m>\pm 3</m>, and <m>\pm 6</m>.  Checking each of these shows that <m>x = -2</m>,            <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 3</m> are roots.  After doing long division, we find the polynomial factors as 
            <me permid="DRw">(x-3)(x+1)(x+2)(x^2+1)</me>.
          This is completely factored over <m>\Q</m> now.  The last quadratic factor is irreducible because if it were to factor, it would factor as linear terms, but it has no roots in <m>\Q</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="lGB">
        <statement>
          <p permid="joL">
          Factor the polynomial <m>x^5 + x^4 + 3x^3 + 3x^2 + 2x + 2</m> completely over <m>\Z_5</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="DoG">
          <p permid="Ocg">
          We start by checking for roots (there are only 5 possibilities in <m>\Z_5</m>).  We find that <m>2</m>,            <m>3</m>, and <m>4</m> are roots.  Dividing by the corresponding factors gives us 
            <me permid="jYF">
            (x-2)(x-3)(x-4)(x^2 + 2) = (x+3)(x+2)(x+1)(x^2+2).
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="RNK">
        <statement>
          <p permid="PvU">
          Factor <m>4x^7 + 10x^4 - 15x^2 + 5</m> completely over <m>\Q</m> (and explain how you know the irreducible factors are irreducible).
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="jvP">
          <p permid="ujp">
          The polynomial is already factored.  It is irreducible over <m>\Q</m> by Eisenstein's criterion using <m>p = 5</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="xUT">
        <statement>
          <p permid="vDd">
          Give an example of a polynomial with integer coefficients which has no roots in <m>\Q</m> but is <em>not</em> irreducible in <m>\Q[x]</m>.  Explain how you know your example works.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="PCY">
          <p permid="aqy">
          Here is such a polynomial: <m>x^4 + 2x^2 + 1 = (x^2 + 1)(x^2+1)</m>.  Clearly it is not irreducible, and the only possible roots are <m>pm 1</m> neither of which are roots.  The point is that because the degree of the polynomial is greater than 3, it could factor as non-linear terms; roots only correspond to linear factors.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="ecc">
        <statement>
          <p permid="bKm">
          Give an example of a polynomial with integer coefficients that is irreducible but that you can't use Eisenstein's criterion to prove is irreducible.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="vKh">
          <p permid="GxH">
          For example, <m>x^2 + 4x + 8</m> must be irreducible, because it is degree 2 and has not roots.  However, the only prime that we could use for Eisenstein's criterion would be <m>p = 2</m> and <m>2^2 = 4</m> divides the constant, so Eisenstein's criterion does not apply.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercises>


