      <exercise permid="WxD">
        <statement>
          <p permid="UfN">
          Prove that the function <m>\phi:\bC \to \bC</m> given by <m>\phi(z) = \bar z</m> is a ring homomorphism.  Here <m>\bar z = a-bi</m> is the complex conjugate of <m>z = a+bi</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="HYz">
          <p permid="MWN">
          Consider the two complex numbers <m>a+bi</m> and <m>c+di</m>.  We have 
            <me permid="hdZ">
            \phi(a+bi)+\phi(c+di) = a-bi + c - di = a+c - (b+d)i = \phi(a+c+(b+d)i) = \phi((a+bi)+(c+di))
            </me>
          and
            <me permid="Nli">
            \phi(a+bi)\phi(c+di) = (a-bi)(c-di) = ac + bd - (cb+ad)i = \phi(ac+bd + (cb+ad)i) = \phi((a+bi)(c+di))
            </me>.       
          </p>
        </solution>
