      <exercise permid="iLV">
        <statement>
          <p permid="guf">
          Is <m>x^7 - 1</m> irreducible over <m>\bC</m>?  How many roots should it have?  Find all of them.  Hint: use the polar form of complex numbers, <m>re^{i\vartheta}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="UmR">
          <p permid="Zlf">
         The polynomial is not irreducible over <m>\bC</m> because the only irreducible polynomials with real coefficients over <m>\bC</m> are the linear polynomials.  It should have exactly 7 roots.  If we write <m>1 = e^0 = e^{2\pi i} = \cdots</m> and raise each to the <m>1/7</m> we get the roots.  They are:
            <me permid="tsr">e^0 = 1, ~~ e^{\frac{2\pi}{7}i}, ~~ e^{\frac{4\pi}{7}i}, ~~ e^{\frac{6\pi}{7}i}, ~~ e^{\frac{8\pi}{7}i}, ~~ e^{\frac{10\pi}{7}i}, ~~ e^{\frac{12\pi}{7}i}</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="OTe">
        <statement>
          <p permid="MBo">
          Factor <m>x^8 - 5x^7 - 14x^6 + x^2 - 5x - 14</m> completely over <m>\Q</m>,            <m>\bC</m> and <m>\R</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="Aua">
          <p permid="Fso">
          First, find rational roots.  They are -2 and 7.  Dividing we get
            <me permid="ZzA">(x+2)(x-7)(x^6+1)</me>
          The last term has no roots but is still not irreducible.  We can use sum of cubes:
            <me permid="FGJ">(x+2)(x-7)(x^2+1)(x^4-x^2 + 1)</me>
          The last degree 4 polynomial is irreducible - use the quadratic formula for <m>x^2</m> to see that there are no quadratic factors over <m>\Q</m>.

          Now let's factor <m>(x^6 + 1)</m> over <m>\bC</m>.  There are 6 roots, namely
            <me permid="lNS">e^{i\pi/6},~~ e^{i3\pi/6}, ~~e^{i5\pi/6},~~ e^{i7\pi/6}, ~~ e^{i9\pi/6}, ~~e^{i11\pi/6}</me>
          These are all <q>nice</q> angles, so it is easy to convert back to rectangular form.  So over <m>\bC</m> we have the factorization
            <me permid="RVb">(x+2)(x-7)(x-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}-\frac{1}{2}i)(x-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{2}i)(x-i)(x+i)(x+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}-\frac{1}{2}i)(x+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{2}i)</me>

          Finally, to get the factorization over <m>\R</m> we multiply conjugate pairs:
            <me permid="yck">(x+2)(x-7)(x^2+1)(x^2 - \sqrt{3}+1)(x^2 + \sqrt{3}x + 1)</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

